[normal]Written evidence 
[normal]submitted by Plan UK
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This submission provides evidence of the 
[normal]need to focus on 
[normal]children with 
[normal]disabilities
[normal] in development
[normal], especially those facing triple discrimination due to their age, gender and disability. 
[normal]It provides evidence from Plan’s research and programmes in developing countries around disability, education and health in order to make recommendations for future ac
[normal]tion. This submission calls for the UK government 
[normal]to
[normal]:
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Develop
[normal] 
[normal]a disability strategy 
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Ensure all children with disabilities have access to a quality education 
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Ensure all children with disabilities are protected from violence
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Ensure all children with disabi
[normal]lities can meaningfully participate in the decisions that affect them 
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Promote and lead on developing better data and information about the lives of children with disabilities
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Plan is a global children’s charity. We work with children 
[normal]in 48 of 
[normal]the world’s poorest countries 
[normal]across three continents 
[normal]to help them build a better future. For 76 years we’ve been taking action and standing up for every child’s righ
[normal]t to fulfil their pote
[normal]ntial by 
[normal]giving children a healthy start in life, includin
[normal]g access to safe drinking water. Alongside
[normal] securing the education of girls and boys, working with communities to pr
[normal]epare for and survive disasters and 
[normal]protect
[normal]ing
[normal] child
[normal]ren from abuse and exploitation
[normal]. We are also inspiring 
[normal]children to take a lead in decisions that affect their lives and enabling families to earn a living and plan for their children’s future.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Plan UK is a rights-based organisation and believes it is every child’s right to have a qual
[normal]ity education. This belief 
[normal]reflects 
[normal]the statements articulated in Article 24 of the Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities which states that p
[normal]ersons with disabilities 
[normal]should not be 
[normal]excluded from the general education system on the basis of d
[normal]isabi
[normal]lity
[normal],
[normal] and p
[normal]ersons with disabilities 
[normal]have the right to 
[normal]access an inclusive, quality and free primary education and secondary education on an equal basis with others in the
[normal] communities in which they live. 
[normal]Article 32 of the 
[normal]Convention on the Rights of Pe[bold]ople with disabilities [bold]calls for 
[normal]states to ensure 
[normal]that international cooperation, including international development programmes, 
[normal]are
[normal] inclusive of and accessib
[normal]le to persons with disabilities. This highlights the need for DFID to ensure a disability strategy is in place across their programmes. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Children with disabilities are often at a double disadvantage, being marginali
[normal]s
[normal]ed and discriminated against because of
[normal] both
[normal] their age and their disability.
[normal] Children are more vulnerable as they are not yet fully developed physically or cognitively. 
[normal]Girls 
[normal]and women 
[normal]with disabilities 
[normal]in particular are at risk when 
[normal]factors such as gender and poverty 
[normal]increase 
[normal]their
[normal] vulnerabili
[normal]ty and marginali
[normal]s
[normal]ation.
[normal] 
[normal]There is therefore a
[normal] need for a specific focus on 
[normal]both 
[normal]girls and boys
[normal] within a disability-inclusive development agenda.
[normal] 
[normal]Note that experiences of disadvantage are not homogeneous across all girls and boys with disabilities, but are 
[normal]strongly mediated by the type of disability
[normal]. F
[normal]or example, Plan research in Sierra Leone showed th
[normal]at
[normal] children with mobility impairments incurred due to war injuries suffered less discrimination than children
[normal] with epilepsy or mental impairments.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Plan receives DFID funding through a 
[normal]Programme Partnership Arrangement (
[normal]PPA
[normal])
[normal] and for 
[normal]a 
[normal]Girls Education Challenge (GEC) fund project in Sierra Leone. 
[normal]The evidence and recommendations 
[normal]on disability integration within DFID will be framed in relation the Girls
[normal] Education Challenge Fund. Wider research from Plan programmes contributes towards the evidence used to support the recommendations. 
[normal]Plan’s DFID funded 
[normal]GEC
[normal] programme in Sierra Leone focusses on reaching the most marginalised groups, including 
[normal]children with
[normal] disabilities
[normal]. The need to reach out to these groups is clear. W
[normal]e will work with 2,052 children with disabilities through partnering with Handicap International (HI), over the three years of the project. It is the largest programme HI have been involved in
[normal] for children with disabilities in Sierra Leone. DFID has said repeatedly that they class the project as innovative due to this element on disability, which reflects the lack of other projects 
[normal]either 
[normal]specifically targeting 
[normal]or mainstreaming 
[normal]disabled groups 
[normal]in this way. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Globally, 
[normal]children with disabilities are
[normal] more likely to experience violence and abuse
[normal] than children without disabilities
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Research conducted in 
[normal]Cameroon, Ethiopia, Senegal, Uganda and Zambia 
[normal]by the African Child Policy Forum, found that the almost 1
[normal],
[normal]000 young people with disabilities had universally experienced, at a minimum, sexual harassment and emotional violence during their childhood. 
[normal]The per
[normal]petrators of violence were often members of their extended family or their peers, making the home and school often unsafe spaces for children with disabilities
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The 
[normal]African Child Policy Forum research found that 
[normal]across the entire sexual violence category,
[normal] girls and boys with disabilities were equally likely to suffer
[normal] sexual violence once or twice (28% of all cases), but girls were far more likely to suffer sexual violence more than 10 times (28%) than boys (16%).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]C
[normal]hildren with disabilities are less 
[normal]likely to attend school
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]Plan’s new 
[normal]report 
[normal]Include Us!
[normal], which 
[normal]conducted research using data from Plan’s sponsored children, 
[normal]c
[normal]oncluded 
[normal]the following
[normal] about the realities faced by children with disabilities in comparison to those without:
[normal]  
[normal]they are 
[normal]substant
[normal]ially less likely to attend school
[normal], will experience a poorer education when in school, and are 
[normal]much more likely to have had a serious illness in the last 12 months, including malnutrit
[normal]ion. C
[normal]hildren with disabilities who do attend school are generally 
[normal]more 
[normal]likely to be overage for their grade than their non disabled 
[normal]peers;
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]research shows that this is often a precursor to drop out.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Within most countries, inclusion levels for children with disabilities in schooling were highest for those with vision or hearing impairments and lowest for those with learning, physical or communication impairments. This indicates that the level of exclus
[normal]ion can be linked to the type of impairment. 
[normal]M
[normal]ore research
[normal] is required to better determine and understand the relationships between type of impairment and school access.
[normal] 
[normal]3.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Plan’s baseline
[normal] research
[normal] for the Girls Education Challenge Fund programme in 
[normal]five d
[normal]istricts in 
[normal]Sierra Leone (to be published) found that
[normal] girls with disabilities experience poorer
[normal] educational outcomes
[normal], school attendance, and retention, than 
[normal]those without disabilities, further legitimizing the need to focus on 
[normal]girls 
[normal]with disabilities 
[normal] in 
[normal]and outside of 
[normal]education.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A s
[normal]tudy from Plan Nepal showed that children with disabilities face specific challenges in accessing health and education services, due to structural, physical and attitudinal barriers
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]A Plan study from West Africa 
[normal]in Togo, Sierra Leone, Niger and Guinea, 
[normal]found that stigma and discrimination against children with disabilities from parents, teachers, community members and policy-makers hinders their access to ed
[normal]ucation and protection services
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]S
[normal]imilar 
[normal]findings were m
[normal]ade through 
[normal]research in Guatemala
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]I
[normal]t is also crucial to note that children with disabilities are more vulnerable in disaster
[normal] 
[normal]situations
[normal], 
[normal]and in these contexts are at increased risk of violations of their rights to
[normal] 
[normal]protection, education and 
[normal]participation.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Access
[normal] to sexual and reproductive health services can be restricted for persons with disabilities. Disabled people are often assumed not to be sexually active
[normal],
[normal] are not believed if they report sexual violence, and are often not appropriately involved in decisions about their sexual and reproductive health
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]People with learning disabilities and difficulties can face additional or heightened risks: 
[normal]such as
[normal], higher
[normal] risks of sexual abuse, assault and rape
[normal],
[normal] lower access to services, support, or redress, and forced sterilisation
[normal].
[normal] D
[normal]isabled children are also much more likely to suffer sexual violence and girls with disabilities are even more vulnerable.
[normal]  Furthermore l
[normal]ack of access to sexual and 
[normal]reproductive health
[normal] services has greater impact upon girls and women.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]For every woman who dies as a result of pregnancy related complications, some twenty others face serious or long-lasting consequences.
[normal] Harmful practices such
[normal] as 
[normal]female genital mutilation (FGM), early and forced marriage
[normal], as well as poor sexual and reproductive health including high 
[normal]and frequent fertility can result
[normal] in disabilities including obstetric fistula and uterine prolapse.  
[normal]Currently an estimated 2 
[normal]million women in Asia and Sub Saharan Africa live with untreated fistula.
[normal] 
[normal]A
[normal]ccording to a WHO multi-country study of 30,000 women on the obstetric effects of FGM, the relative risk of adverse maternal outcomes increased for women with FGM I, II or II as co
[normal]mpared to women without FGM. Risks seem to be greater with more extensive FGM.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Sexual Violence[bold]: 
[normal]The risk of depression and anxiety
[normal] is three to four times higher for those who have experienced 
[normal]gender-based violence
[normal], and around a third of all survivors of 
[normal]rape experience 
[normal]Posttraumatic Stress Disorder
[normal].
[normal]  Sexual violence can result in acute and chronic physical disabilities, for example 
[normal]severe pain during menstruation 
[normal]or prolonged menstrual bleeding, as well as long term 
[normal]genital-anal trauma
[normal] and
[normal] sexually trans
[normal]mitted infections
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Plan UK recognises the work DFID has done on disability in the last 10 years, DFID’s work has placed the issue on the global development agenda. 
[normal]This would be strengthened by a strategy 
[normal]for 
[normal]the integration of 
[normal]disability 
[normal]issues 
[normal]across all its projects.
[normal] DFID’s
[normal] recent commitments on disability are welcomed by Plan UK as they are an important signal to developing country partners and other donors to pr
[normal]ioritise disabled people. Plan has seen this commitment through its GEC programme funding. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Plan’s GEC programme interventions focus on poor rural girls, within this group, girls with disabilities are more marginalised with 76% estimated to be out of scho
[normal]ol
[normal] due to discrimination, stigma and a lack of inclusive education opportunities, adequately trained teachers or accessible facilities. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Community Based Rehabilitation (CBR) approach involves the whole community to foster educational inclusion. Disab
[normal]ility will be mainstreamed through all interventions and accessibility needs addressed in terms of materials, communication and venue selection where relevant. It is assumed that 
[normal]children with disabilities
[normal] are even l
[normal]ess likely to reach the end of p
[normal]rimary S
[normal]chool and make the transition to 
[normal]junior secondary school
[normal], and therefore most of the direct support for disabled children with focus on their enrolling/re-enrolling in Primary.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We are early on in the programme but we have some lessons learnt already, including that working with children with disabilities in a rural setting is 
[normal]a more 
[normal]resource intensive exercise
[normal] than anticipated
[normal]. 
[normal]Children with disabilities
[normal] are often 
[normal]hidden by famil
[normal]ies, and to ensu
[normal]re their specific needs are met requires specialist expertise and raising community awareness of  
[normal]the 
[normal]rights
[normal] of children with disabilities
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Case Study:[bold] 
[normal]Children with disabilities[bold] pushed out of school[bold]. One 
[normal]child with disability 
[normal]in Kailahun
[normal],
[normal] Sierra Leone
[normal] was a girl 
[normal]with albinism 
[normal]who had 
[normal]a visual impairment
[normal]. She was no longer in school. She had hoped to 
[normal]pass junior secondary school three
[normal], and was determined to make it as far as the disability would allow. Then, she got pregnant. She told her 
[normal]interviewer, “Yes I have been mistreated sexually and physically and also insulted by my teachers and colleagues in school. When I decided to leave school it was because I was impregnated by some guys I didn't know. Because of my poor eyesight I can’t reme
[normal]mber them, so they denied responsibility.” After she became pregnant the school refused to let her continue.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]5.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Data: [bold]The 
[normal]number 
[normal]of 
[normal]girls with disabilities 
[normal]reported in Plan’s baseline household survey 
[normal]are 
[normal]likely to be much lower than 
[normal]in reality
[normal]. T
[normal]his reflect
[normal]s the lack of 
[normal]data available on 
[normal]children with disabilities
[normal], due to their exclusion
[normal] and the underreporting by community members due to stigma and lack of awareness. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Attitudes[bold]:[bold] [bold]Plan’s 
[normal]baseline survey
[normal] for the GEC
[normal] 
[normal]was a
[normal]lso revealing 
[normal]around 
[normal]non disabled schoo
[normal]l age 
[normal]girls’ 
[normal]attitudes
[normal] 
[normal]on
[normal] 
[normal]the
[normal] education
[normal] of children with disabilities
[normal]. 
[normal]A
[normal] majority of girls believe it 
[normal]is okay for children who have d
[normal]isabilities 
[normal]not 
[normal]to 
[normal]go to school
[normal]. 23
[normal]% of 
[normal]girls who have physical disabilities believe that it is okay for 
[normal]girls like themsel
[normal]ves 
[normal]not
[normal] to
[normal] get an education
[normal]. This might indicate the way 
[normal]children with disabilities 
[normal] are treated in school,
[normal] 
[normal]if their colleagues do not believe it is important for them to be there, and more than that, are contributing to  perception of themselves as not worthy of 
[normal]being at 
[normal]school.
[normal] This also illustrates the wider community’s perceptions of the value and capabiliti
[normal]es 
[normal]of children with disabilities,
[normal] much of the internalisation of these perceptions will start at a young age
