[normal]s the first step to inclusion. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]5.8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Children with [bold]disabilities [bold]face[bold] discrimination and abuse in school [bold]Nearly every single child with disability  interviewed in each district 
[normal]identified 
[normal]verbal and physical harassment as  the main reason for lea
[normal]ving school. Many also said that they (or their parents) had brought the abuse to their teachers’ attention, but intervention (if any) had been ineffective. A 
[normal]girl with disability 
[normal] in Moyamba noted “only my colleagues would disturb and mock me. I do report
[normal] to the teachers so the teacher 
[normal]in return will flog the people. M
[normal]y colleagues laugh at me because I am unable to talk, so that made me drop out of school.” Some
[normal] children with disabilities
[normal] even described abuse from the teachers themselves
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Overall recommendation: [bold]Plan 
[normal]UK 
[normal]is calling for DFID 
[normal]to 
[normal]develop an overarching disability inclusive development strategy
[normal], with focus areas including access to quality education, protection from violence and meaningful participation in decisions and 
[normal]across its work
[normal] 
[normal]with 
[normal]children with disabilities 
[normal]to focus on 
[normal]those most vulnerable 
[normal]as a result of 
[normal]intersecting inequalities incl
[normal]uding gender and poverty.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Disability strategy [bold]Plan UK supports the recommendations made by the Global Campaign for Education and the Bond Disability and Development group for DFID to implement a twin-track approach to disability which would involve: 
[normal]Development of such a strategy must be done through a process of consultation with persons with disabilities, including children. 
[normal]6.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Ensure c[bold]hildren with disabilities [bold]have access [bold]to [bold]a [bold]quality [bold]education. [bold]A quality education is one that is grounded in respect for human rights and gender equity, that is accessible to all children without discrimination, and one in which all children are encouraged to fulfil their 
[normal]capabilities.  It includes a learning environ
[normal]ment that is learner-friendly, safe and healthy for all children with mechanisms to prevent and respond to violence.  A quality education is accountable to children through the participation of children, families and communities in school governance and de
[normal]cision –making. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Activities required to ensure this include 
[normal]training
[normal] for
[normal] all
[normal] teachers to ensure they can support the education of children with disabilities. 
[normal]C
[normal]urriculum adaptation and improved accessibility
[normal] are also required
[normal], alongside raising public awar
[normal]eness on the rights to quality education for all children
[normal] and initiatives to challenge discrimination against children with disabilities within the school community
[normal].
[normal] Children with disabilities should also have access to
[normal] 
[normal]early childhood care and development [bold](ECCD), which 
[normal]has been 
[normal]shown to provide immense benefits for children throughout life
[normal] and to 
[normal]help them 
[normal]reach their full potential
[normal]. Inclusive ECCD is also a critical pathway to education
[normal] alongside the resources, both mat
[normal]erial and capacity building needed to integrate inclusive education into all teacher training
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]All [bold]children with disabilities[bold] are p[bold]rotect[bold]ed from violence:[bold] both within a
[normal]nd outside of school contexts, 
[normal]r
[normal]ights 
[normal]of 
[normal]c
[normal]hildren with disabilities 
[normal]to protection from violence 
[normal]m
[normal]ust be secured. P
[normal]rotection 
[normal]systems
[normal] 
[normal]need to be
[normal] resourced to focus on 
[normal]and be accessible to 
[normal]the most vulnerable
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]All [bold]children with disabilities [bold]can [bold]meaningfully participate in decisions that affect them[bold] [bold]- 
[normal]unless girls and boys w
[normal]ith disabilities are consulted and involved in the design, implementation and monitoring of interventions across all sectors then 
[normal]the interventions
[normal] 
[normal]will not meet their needs and 
[normal]children with disabilities 
[normal]will be left behind.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Improve [bold]data[bold] collection[bold] - [bold]DFID’s focus on the data revolution can be used to address the paucity of data on children with disabilities. 
[normal]Plan supports the recommendation made by 
[normal]UNICEF in 
[normal]its report 
[normal]T
[normal]he
[normal] 
[normal]State of the World’s Children: Children with Disabilities
[normal] that for children with
[normal] disabilities
[normal], ‘
[normal]many of their deprivations stem from and are perpetuated by their invisibility
[normal]… 
[normal]there is a need for research to render more children visible by improvi
[normal]ng data collection and analysis’
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Research 
[normal]on people with disabilities 
[normal]should be disaggr
[normal]egated 
[normal]by 
[normal]age, 
[normal]gender
[normal], location, wealth quintile and type of impairment. This data 
[normal]should be used to track the progress of disadvantaged and marginalised groups across all goals, targets and indicators
[normal] within the post-2015 framework
[normal]. T
[normal]he negotiations 
[normal]around the post-
[normal]2015 development framework are a key moment for the UK government, DFID and FCO to push for this change to data collection within the framework.
